body:
### Description

I have a parent schema which has defined two `oneOf`s and two properties. One property is used as the discriminator the other property should be inherited by the schemas which are defined as `oneOf`. To achieve this the `oneOf`-schemas are using an `allOf` definition. The parent schema is generated as enum and the child schemas are generated as structs.

The problem I have is that the properties of the parent scheme are missing. They are not included in the `oneOf` structs. The `allOf` seems to produce just some kind of cyclic reference here.

### Reproduction

This is my OAS:  
```yaml
openapi: 3.0.3
info: {title: Test, version: 1.0.0}
servers:
  - {url: 'https://test'}
paths:
  /v1/test:
    get:
      responses:
        '200':
          description: OK
          content:
            application/json;charset=UTF-8:
              schema:
                type: array
                items: {$ref: '#/components/schemas/Parent'}
components:
  schemas:
    Parent:
      type: object
      oneOf:
        - {$ref: '#/components/schemas/Child1'}
        - {$ref: '#/components/schemas/Child2'}
      discriminator: {propertyName: childrenType}
      properties:
        childrenType: {type: string}
        parentKey: {type: string}
      required: [childrenType, parentKey]

    Child1:
      allOf:
        - {$ref: '#/components/schemas/Parent'}
        - type: object
          properties:
            childDescription: {type: string}

    Child2:
      allOf:
        - {$ref: '#/components/schemas/Parent'}
        - type: object
          properties:
            childDescription: {type: string}
```

And this is the code which gets generated:
```swift
public enum Components {
    public enum Schemas {
        @frozen public indirect enum Parent: Codable, Hashable, Sendable {
            case child1(Components.Schemas.Child1)
            case child2(Components.Schemas.Child2)
            /// ...
        }

        public struct Child1: Codable, Hashable, Sendable {
            public var value1: Components.Schemas.Parent
            public struct Value2Payload: Codable, Hashable, Sendable {
                public var childDescription: Swift.String?
                /// ...
            }
            public var value2: Components.Schemas.Child1.Value2Payload
            /// ...
        }

        public struct Child2: Codable, Hashable, Sendable {
            public var value1: Components.Schemas.Parent
            public struct Value2Payload: Codable, Hashable, Sendable {
                public var childDescription: Swift.String?
                /// ...
            }
            public var value2: Components.Schemas.Child2.Value2Payload
            /// ...
        }
    }
}
```

### Package version(s)

```console
swift-openapi-generator: 1.10.4
swift-openapi-runtime: 1.10.1
swift-openapi-urlsession: 1.2.0
```

### Expected behavior

I would expect the structs `Child1` and `Child2` to have the `parentKey` property. And maybe the `Parent` enum to have the `parentKey` as a computed property which returns the value of the child structs.

### Environment

```console
swift-driver version: 1.127.15 Apple Swift version 6.2.4 (swiftlang-6.2.4.1.4 clang-1700.6.4.2)
Target: arm64-apple-macosx26.0
```

### Additional information

I don't know if I'm trying something totally crazy here. I just have a huge OAS with many such definitions and I want to change as little as possible. I already tried `OpenAPITools/openapi-generator` which adds `parentKey` to `Child1` and `Child2`. But that generator fall short on other places.
